CARMEN XXI.

The history of L. Valerius Messalla Corvinus, of his learning and eloquence, and the origin of his double cognomen, under both of which he appears in Horace's poema, are fully given in Smith’s Dict. Biog. The date of this ode, which is addressed to the testa containing the wine intended sor Messalla at a supper to which he has invited himself at Horace’s house, cannot by any sort of evidence be oven conjectured. Dillenbr. says it was a song composed extempore at a party at which Messalla was symposiarch. In such extemporaneous effusions Dillenbr. puts more faith than 1 can3 but the ode may have

been recited at the supper-table, and composed for the occasion it professes to have been composed for.

Liber, Venus, and the Gracoe shall keep thee company till the dawn of day.
